🔹 What is ExecutorService in Java?

ExecutorService is an interface from:

📦 java.util.concurrent

It is used to:

✅ Manage and control a pool of threads
✅ Execute tasks asynchronously
✅ Reuse threads instead of creating new ones

It is an advanced version of Executor.

🔥 Why Not Create Threads Manually?

Instead of:

new Thread(() -> {
    // task
}).start();

Problems:

Creates new thread every time ❌

High memory usage ❌

Hard to manage ❌

No lifecycle control ❌

So Java introduced Executor Framework.

🔹 How to Create ExecutorService

Most common way:

ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2);

Other options:

Method	Description
newFixedThreadPool(n)	Fixed number of threads
newCachedThreadPool()	Creates threads as needed
newSingleThreadExecutor()	Only one thread
newScheduledThreadPool(n)	For delayed/scheduled tasks
🔹 Basic Example
import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;
import java.util.concurrent.Executors;

public class ExecutorExample {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2);

        executor.submit(() -> {
            System.out.println("Task executed by: " +
                    Thread.currentThread().getName());
        });

        executor.shutdown();
    }
}
🔹 Important Methods
Method	Purpose
submit()	Submit task (returns Future)
execute()	Run task (no return)
shutdown()	Stop accepting new tasks
shutdownNow()	Stop immediately
awaitTermination()	Wait for completion
🔥 submit() vs execute()
execute()

Returns nothing

Used for Runnable

submit()

Returns Future

Can get result

Example with return value:

ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(1);

Future<Integer> future = executor.submit(() -> {
    return 10 + 20;
});

System.out.println("Result: " + future.get());

executor.shutdown();
🔹 What is Future?

Future represents the result of asynchronous computation.

You can:

Check if done

Get result

Cancel task

🔥 Internal Working

Behind the scenes:

ExecutorService uses:

👉 ThreadPoolExecutor

Structure:

Task → Queue → Thread → Execution
🔴 Very Important for You (Spring Boot Developer)

In Spring Boot:

@Async

ThreadPoolTaskExecutor

Web request handling

All use ExecutorService internally.

🔥 ThreadLocal + ExecutorService Danger

Since threads are reused in pool:

If you forget:

threadLocal.remove();

Data can leak between tasks.

Very common interview question.

🏆 Interview Definition

ExecutorService is a sub-interface of Executor that manages a pool of threads and provides methods to submit tasks,
control execution, and retrieve results asynchronously.

Threads are not newly created.

So inheritance does not happen.

That’s why frameworks like Spring Security do not rely only on InheritableThreadLocal in thread pools.
